headline: Impeachment train keeps rolling with testimony from David Holmes, Fiona Hill
subHeadline: 'The Five' react to the biggest moments from day five of the public impeachment hearings on Capitol Hill.

utterances.speaker: JUAN WILLIAMS, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Hello, everyone. I'm Juan Williams, along with Emily Compagno, Jesse Waters, Dana Perino and Greg Gutfeld. It's 5:00 in New York City. This is The Five. Another blockbuster day of impeachment hearings on Capitol Hill. Former National Security Council official Fiona Hill testifying, as well as David Holmes, the State Department aide who overheard President Trump and Ambassador Gordon Sondland's July 26 phone call in the Ukraine. Fireworks erupting early on today when Fiona Hill clashed with Republicans over claims of Ukrainian 2016 election interference:

utterances.speaker: FIONA HILL
utterances.sentences: Some of you on this committee appear to believe that Russia and its security services did not conduct a campaign against our country and that perhaps somehow, for some reason, Ukraine did. This is a fictional narrative that has been perpetrated and propagated by the Russian security services themselves.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.sentences: The 240-page report analyzed 2016 Russian meddling campaign. I asked my staff to hand these reports to our two witnesses today. Needless to say, it is entirely possible for two separate nations to engage in election meddling at the same time. And Republicans believe we should take meddling seriously by all foreign countries, regardless of which campaign is the target.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: And here's David Holmes recalling Ambassador Sondland's phone call with President Trump:

utterances.speaker: DAVID HOLMES
utterances.sentences: Was quite loud when the president came on, quite distinctive. When the president came on, he sort of winced and held the phone away from his ear like this. And then Ambassador Sondland said, said "he loves your ass. Will do whatever you want." He said he can do the investigation.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.sentences: What was Ambassador Sondland's response?

utterances.speaker: DAVID HOLMES
utterances.sentences: He said, "oh, yeah, he's going to do it. He'll do anything you ask."

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: President Trump tweeting his defense of that call. "I've been watching people make phone calls my entire life. My hearing is and has been great. Never have I been watching a person make a call which was not on a speaker phone and been able to hear or understand a conversation. I've even tried, but to no avail. Try it live." What do you say, Jesse?

utterances.speaker: JESSE WATTERS, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Well, some people say that Trump's hearing is his best attribute, Juan.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Is that right?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I also will say this.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Wait, was that a put down of the president?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: No.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, OK.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: The hoax is over. It's done. Whole thing's up in smoke. I mean, you guys tried. You failed. You didn't have one witness to testify that Trump directed a quid pro quo involving military aid. Not one. So, let's go home. Let's just forget it all happened. Nancy Pelosi wasted everyone's time. What did she do in 2019, Juan? She got bullied by AOC, she shut down the government, and then she failed to impeach the president. We're going to look back at 2019 like "what? You did nothing." No NAFTA renegotiation, no drug prices, no infrastructure. What happened today? Someone overheard a phone call? So what? He eavesdropped? The president said, "I don't give a blank about Ukraine." Well, neither does the country. The other one had a great accent. Why was she even there? I mean, this is the reason Trump is dual tracking diplomacy in Ukraine in the first place because of people like Fiona, because Fiona doesn't even know there was Ukraine collusion. I mean, she actually met Christopher Steele and saw the dossier before the dossier went public. I mean, the whole thing comes down to this. Trump's vision aligns with populism, skeptical of foreign aid, and doesn't like these swampy Joe Biden type deals. So, we're looking at this. This is the best you got? Try again.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Alright. So, let's -- in fact, you mentioned Nancy Pelosi, the speaker. Let's listen to what Nancy Pelosi had to say:

utterances.speaker: SPEAKER NANCY PELOSI
utterances.sentences: The Republicans are in denial about the facts. If the Republicans do not want to honor their oath of office and then I don't think the dispute should be -- we should be characterized as partisan in any way because we are patriotic.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: So today we heard from Fiona Hill, Dana, who said that John Bolton, who was the national security adviser for President Trump, knew what was going on, warned her to stay out of domestic politics, that they were handling international affairs, foreign affairs. You can't say that John Bolton's a never-Trumper. You can't say that he's a Democrat. And yet he was very leery of this effect. You know, he said at one point, this is their drug deal, talking about Rudy and the gang.

utterances.speaker: DANA PERINO, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: So, one thing I would say is I feel like John Bolton was a really good boss because he was looking out for his people. He didn't want to get them into a situation where they ultimately ended up, which is testifying in front of Congress about something that they didn't really have anything to do with that they were just [unintelligible] witnesses, too, but that they have to hire lawyers. They have to take time out of their work. They have to come there and be humiliated by Republicans and Democrats who just want to make speeches and be rude about them. The thing about Fiona Hill is that in her deposition, she testified that the Steele dossier was ridiculous. That might not be the word, but she said that it was discredited. The Republicans don't ask her to talk about that today in the hearing. I think on some of the cross-examination, they went after her for things that were a little bit strange. She was actually defending the president on several things. She said, for example, that too could be understood that the president would be frustrated.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Dana, why don't we hear it?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Better to hear it from her than me, yes.

utterances.speaker: GREG GUTFELD, CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: She has a nice voice.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, you like that?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Great accent.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I don't see that.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.sentences: During your deposition, I ask you, was Christopher Steele's dossier a rabbit hole? Do you remember the answer you gave to --.

utterances.speaker: FIONA HILL
utterances.sentences: Yes, I thought it was a rabbit hole.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.sentences: Yeah. And you also said a couple of pages later in the deposition or in the transcript that I have here of your deposition that you thought he got played. Is that fair?

utterances.speaker: FIONA HILL
utterances.sentences: That is fair, yes.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Dana?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: During the deposition, she went deeper into it. But if that was one of their goals, they didn't dwell on it. She also defended Elise Stefanik from attacks because she talked about how she was attacked because she was called angry at some point when she said, actually, I'm just doing my job. She said also that it could be understood -- she absolutely understood that the president would be very hurt and frustrated by the fact that there were all these heads of state and people in the government in Europe who were dissing him in 2015 and 2016, but that that did not affect the way that he dealt with those countries. I thought that was a super strong defense of the president. And yet there they were one by one, just trying to knock her down and I'm like, wait, why are you doing that to somebody who is actually trying to help you?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Alright. So, in fact, though, the RNC is running an ad attacking the hearings. Here it is.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.sentences: This is about preventing a potentially disastrous outcome from occurring next year.

utterances.speaker: DINA TITUS
utterances.sentences: I'd like to impeach the bastard right now.

utterances.speaker: NANCY PELOSI
utterances.sentences: An imposter.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.sentences: He really should be punished.

utterances.speaker: MALE SPEAKER
utterances.sentences: That charlatan in the White House.

utterances.speaker: RASHIDA TLAIB
utterances.sentences: We're going to impeach the motherf____r.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.sentences: I am not running for anything except the impeachment of Trump.

utterances.speaker: FEMALE SPEAKER
utterances.sentences: We cannot accept a second term for Donald Trump.

utterances.speaker: AL GREEN
utterances.sentences: If we don't impeach this president, he will get reelected.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Greg?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah. That's a great ad because now we know this, that the same people that are saying they want Trump out now have always wanted Trump out. You can't take them seriously because this has been their narrative. It's like dating somebody new. Would you take advice from the person you just dumped? No, because they have too much emotional investment in the past. And the emotional investment here is the hatred of Trump. You think of Pelosi saying something about just recently and we showed about being nonpartisan. She's like the real estate agent pretending to be objective when she gives you a tour of an unmitigated dump and saying, oh, it's a charming fixer upper. No, this is a dump. All right. I think that this is going to be a huge boon to Trump. We're already seeing it in the swing states, and I think they might be setting him up for a landslide. It's like when you watch a running back, like Franco Harris or Earl Campbell going towards the end zone carrying seven or eight people. The resistance becomes the momentum. He is turning the resistance into momentum that is carrying him forward. That's a football analogy, America.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Hey, Emily.

utterances.speaker: EMILY COMPAGNO, GUEST CO-HOST
utterances.sentences: Beast mode. Well, if I can just say that what I thought was peeled back today was a really interesting illustration of how important process and old guard and new guard is to a lot of these structures. And I was brought in when I was a federal managing attorney to a certain office and essentially to clean house. But what I was doing was inheriting an existing structure and an existing process and trying to kind of put a new guard in. And it is a struggle that it's really difficult to convey, I think, the weight of that old guard and the weight of the process and how strongly, as we saw today, for example, and most especially from Dr. Hill, who says, look, this is the way that we are used to and the reason we are is because it works. So the question for Americans and for right now, congressmen, is whether or not the disruption of that process is in a way that they find impeachable.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Impeachable?  You mean whether or not the evidence presented this week, the Sondland testimony about quid pro quo? The people say that's enough or not enough. What do you say?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: Whether these representatives feel that in this fact-finding week, that they have enough to go on to make their informed decisions, personally representing their constituents to make the vote. That would be the next step.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: All right. Up next, more reaction to this week's impeachment hearings.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Impeachment circus wrapping up this week as the media continues to embarrass themselves over and over again, every hour of coverage contains some kind of bombshell or it's explosive testimony. But the next one really takes the cake. CNN's Chris Cuomo clearly inspired by my highly acclaimed mom text series. Why are you laughing? So, he called his own mom on live TV to prove how easy it is to overhear a call like today's witness claims he did with Trump. Listen:

utterances.speaker: CHRIS CUOMO
utterances.sentences: Can you just say hello? Mom. She probably can't hear me. Mom, can you hear me?

utterances.speaker: MATILDA CUOMO
utterances.sentences: Yes, I hear you. When you talk to me, I hear you.

utterances.speaker: CHRIS CUOMO
utterances.sentences: I'm talking to you. Say hello to Dana Bash.

utterances.speaker: DANA BASH
utterances.sentences: Hi, Mrs. Cuomo. How are you?

utterances.speaker: CHRIS CUOMO
utterances.sentences: All right.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That's gold, Greg. I don't know his best part of the coverage.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Chris Cuomo is the master of the self own. Whenever he goes for a joke, he's incapable of seeing that he's the butt of his own jokes, which makes me laugh. But you know what I mean, to your point about everything like an explosive turning point. This is going to be the day that changes everything. This is porn for people who lost their sex drive in 2016.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: There's a pill for that, I think.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: think it advertises on Fox.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: All right, Dana, one of the reasons I think that they haven't been able to persuade not only Republicans, but the regular American people is because you can watch these hearings yourself. You could see them. You don't need to hear CNN or ABC tell you what to think. You can watch. And if you watch just for an hour, you don't see bombshells. You don't see explosive testimony. So, you know, you're being lied to when you tune in later for analysis.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: So, yeah, it's interesting because so Fox News has had tremendous viewership throughout this entire thing. And it's not because we've been on TV the entire time, even though I'm sure that's why they would like to tune in. People are genuinely interested. The results so far that have come back from the public opinion surveys about how they're feeling about impeachment, both nationally and in some of the battleground states have shown that the Democrats are basically not persuading America that the president should be impeached. And I don't think that means that there's not going to be a close election, or it could mean that the president ultimately wins in a landslide. It's too early to tell. But I think that most voters are thinking, let's move on, let's fight this out in November of 2020.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: 'Yeah. Juan, one of the reasons -- it's not a persuadable case, it's very complex. There's a lot of different layers. You have WMD, Watergate, Lewinsky, Iran Contra -- you can explain that to an eight-year-old, maybe not the Lewinsky thing, but you can expect that to a very young person. This, you know, you can watch hours of this hearing and you still don't know what's going.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Really?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Yeah. Even the people testifying don't know what's going on.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Oh, that's clear from your perspective.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Sondland yesterday -- I don't know what was up.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: I'll tell you what struck me today was Republicans stop questioning Hill and Holmes. Instead, they went into these kinds of partisan rants. And it was like at the end that they're just ranting at the witness because they don't want to hear anything to do with facts. It's like Republicans -- oh, she didn't have a fact?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: -- she got fired this summer before the whole thing started.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: She had a lot of facts. She had a lot of --.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: She got fired a long time.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Dana's upset.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: I'm not upset.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Okay. I thought -- you said you don't like her being tracked. I don't like her being tracked because -- she was a strong candidate. I think witness Yovanovitch strong. What Fiona Hill said was, I'm here as a fact witness. It's up to you, the Congress, to decide about impeachment. But she said, you know what? I chose to go into the Trump administration. Here's what happened with my boss, John Bolton. Here's what I heard. Here's meetings I went into to say, you guys can't do this here. It's inappropriate. You're pursuing a separate channel. And then to hear how she was attacked, how she is said to be -- I think it's Roger Stone and Alex Jones. Oh, she's a George Soros plant. Well, I mean, this is just --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I don't know if she's a George Soros plan. I think when she says I don't like politics, Emily, getting involved in diplomacy, I mean, Barack Obama pulled out of -- he lied about Benghazi. Barack Obama spied on Donald Trump -- politics. No one blew the whistle then.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: The only way to find the whistle was too short. Listen, here is what happened in the federal government while the viewers of mainstream media were subjected to these impeachment hearings and our tax dollars are pouring in. We what we did this week on Wednesday, the Senate confirmed the first Cuban American woman judge of the 11th Circuit, which shifted that balance toward the GOP's favor. And that's the third court that has been shifted and flipped during this administration. That's a big deal. A veteran suicide bill made great strides this week as well. And in a state that really matters for this election, which is Wisconsin. We got that poll that came out yesterday that said Trump is head-to-head or surpassed all of the Dems that are leading and most importantly, the majority of voters there oppose impeachment. So, in a state that really matters, no one cares about this.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: Alright. We're going to move on from impeachment, alright? Because the Democrats had a debate last night. You might not even know. Greg has got the whole thing next.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: The clown car rolled into Atlanta, dropping off a pile of broken toys minus the batteries. There was Gramps, who sounded like a 10-year-old coming down from the laughing gas after getting a tooth pulled:

utterances.speaker: JOE BIDEN
utterances.sentences: The next president of the United States is going to have to do to two things. Defeat Donald Trump. That's number one. And number two, it's going to have to be able to go into states like Georgia and North Carolina and other places and get a Senate majority.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Maybe it's not his fault. He did just find out he was a grandfather. Then there was the cop pretending to be something she's not:

utterances.speaker: KAMALA HARRIS
utterances.sentences: I think that it's unfortunate that we have someone on the stage who is attempting to be the Democratic nominee for president of the United States, who during the Obama administration spent four years full-time on Fox News criticizing President Obama.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah, it's unfortunate to have the guts to go on TV and face tough questions. Maybe you should throw her in jail. And who is this guy again?

utterances.speaker: TOM STEYER
utterances.sentences: But I'm different from everybody else on this stage. I'm the only person on this stage who will say that climate is the number one priority for me. I'm the only person on this stage who's spent decades building an international business. I'm the person who can do it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Did someone leave John Kerry out in the sun? God, I miss Marianne and Swalwell. It would have been a gas. Dana. Yeah. But thank God they focused on child welfare.

utterances.speaker: AMY KLOBUCHAR
utterances.sentences: We should codify Roe v. Wade into law.

utterances.speaker: BERNIE SANDERS
utterances.sentences: Understand that it's women who control their own bodies, not politicians.

utterances.speaker: CORY BOOKER
utterances.sentences: This is a voting issue. This is a voter suppression issue.

utterances.speaker: ELIZABETH WARREN
utterances.sentences: I believe that abortion rights are human rights.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Nice. Yeah. In case you forgot, for Dems, abortion is the ultimate childcare. No need for a babysitter when there's no baby to sit. Bottom line, you could have found more fire in a bag of prunes. Impeachment theater drained them of energy and intelligence, leaving them all searching for something to say to each other than "orange man bad." None of them laid a glove on the other, which is good hygiene. But you know what the debate stage really was? It was that cabin at Camp Crystal Lake from Friday the 13th. And all of those candidates are the stupid teenagers making idiotic decisions. Let's check out the basement. Let's go skinny dipping alone. Above all, don't hop in that car to escape. And Trump. He's the ever-present Jason waiting to pick each and every one of them off. He's there on that stage, even when he isn't. You know, it's sad to think that someday Trump will not be president and the whole world will look like a Democratic debate. But like Jason, maybe we'll just keep bringing him back. Let's look at the positives. Juan, I thought Booker won. I thought that he expressed energy and brains, like he could be on stage. But do you think it's too late for him?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: No, it's not too late, because I think this is up in the air in many ways. But I don't know why you thought he won. If you were saying, oh, you know what, finally, one of the Democrats defended the rich because what he said was Elizabeth Warren going after, you know, a wealth tax on the rich, two percent on people who have billions and all -- he said, well, wait a second, no, the real way to do this to appeal to voters is to talk about wealth creation. How can we help you to become rich and the like? But I thought he was pretty much a non-factor early on, he didn't get much airtime. And I thought that if you were looking for a winner and loser scenario, I would say Pete Buttigieg, who is now the front runner in Iowa, at least, I don't think anybody went after him. I thought that Elizabeth Warren, again, it's not that she made any breakthroughs, but she stood there, and I think she occupied a lot of time, spoke a lot. And Bernie, again, I just don't think it changed anything. And if you look at the ratings, I don't think many people were --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That's true. Jesse, it really kind of just laid there flat when you were watching it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I was actually laying flat while I was watching it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: I thought it was the worst debate so far. I thought it was pathetic, bunch of platitudes. These people are unwatchable. They're boring. No one's breaking through with any clear policy. There's no, even, soundbites or sharp exchanges. I mean, they're talking about climate refugees? What is a climate refugee? It's too hot somewhere, so you pack up and move north? I mean, these things aren't real things that people care about in this country. I heard Biden answer that first question and I thought to myself, it's officially over for him. He had some dark energy going on last night. He looked medicated. I don't know what was coming out of his mouth. Bernie, you know, what you see is what you get. "The billionaires, the billion --" You know, OK. We know, Bernie, you hate billionaires. I mean and what's Biden doing punching down to Tom Steyer? Why is Kamala Harris punching down to Tulsi Gabbard? It's like these people don't even know how to win elections. Mayor Pete sitting there at 5 foot 3, you know, all polished. No one's laying a glove on him. He's surging. And they're not even pretending like they know what they're doing. Who is it? Booker acts like Barney, you know, the big purple guy, the cartoon. He's surprised that everything. Oh, gosh. Oh, golly. I mean, these are not really impressive candidates. And I think this impeachment thing is actually enhanced Donald Trump's aura. I mean, he's out there besieged by enemies, slaying dragons, slapping around China, killing terrorists. And these people are squabbling over climate refugees. So, it's over.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Emily, what do you -- anything to add to that?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: I think that said it all.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Yeah, really.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: I felt like it was like when you see a sequel to a movie that just totally repeats the original movie, and it's so frustrating. And you're like this. There's nothing new.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: It's like Oceans 55.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: No wait, wait. What about when Booker said that Biden must have been high when he said.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That was a great one.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.sentences: That was a good line.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Ahhh, ok, so you did watch.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: I did think it illustrated a little bit, but, probably --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: That's why I said it was good. Go ahead.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: But probably not to the extent that we didn't know already. But who gets flustered and who would shine or could hold their own, I should say, against President Trump?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah, Dana?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.sentences: That's what I felt like.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Two people. I think on Yang, he's like one of the only guys that's talking to, one of the only candidates, who is talking to the suburbs directly.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Like he understands the suburbs anxiety. He speaks to it, and he has ideas for how to deal with their anxieties, whether you like them or not. But he has talking to them that suburban group. And I think that's how he's able to maintain this like five or six percent. He's not going to be the nominee. But he sticks out there. And Mayor Pete seems to be the only one that is able to ad lib an attack.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Everybody else has things that are like well written out for them, so then they know when they're going to, you know, queue my line.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: It was hard to imagine last night how any of them gets to 270 electoral votes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.sentences: Yeah, interesting. But we're going to do it again in the next block. Coming up, Joe Biden's gaffes were so bad at the debate, even Democrats are calling him out.

utterances.speaker: JOE BIDEN
utterances.sentences: No man has a right to raise a hand to a woman in anger other than in self-defense. We have to change the culture, period, and keep punching at it and punching at it and punching at it. There will be a big -- I really mean it. I'm part of that Obama coalition. I come out of the black community in terms of my support. Three former chairs of the Black Caucus, the only African-American woman that had ever been elected to the United States Senate. A whole range of people.

utterances.speaker: CORY BOOKER
utterances.sentences: That's not true. That's not true.

utterances.speaker: KAMALA HARRIS
utterances.sentences: The other one is here.

utterances.speaker: JOE BIDEN
utterances.sentences: I said the first. I said the first African-American --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: Joe Biden being criticized for those gaffes during the debate, including from people in his own party. Former Obama adviser David Axelrod giving this harsh assessment.

utterances.speaker: DAVID AXELROD
utterances.sentences: I wouldn't say that he was a house of fire in any of the debates that we've been been to. And yet he comes kind of bumps along, you know, kind of Mr. Magoo wing his way through this. And you keep worrying that he's going to hit a wall. But he's moving forward.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.sentences: And there it is true. He continues to move forward. Juan, his the early state polls, Iowa, New Hampshire, not so good. But across the board, you look at South Carolina in the national polls. Voters seem to think that he is the most electable against Donald Trump. That seems to be what they believe.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.sentences: Right. And as he pointed out, Donald Trump is making the case for him. In that phone call with Zelensky, he says he wants dirt on not Bernie Sanders, not Elizabeth Warren. He wants dirt on guess who? Joe Biden.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS

You can't take them seriously because this has been their narrative. It's like dating somebody new. Would you take advice from the person you just dumped? No, because they have too much emotional investment in the past. And the emotional investment here is the hatred of Trump. You think of Pelosi saying something about just recently and we showed about being nonpartisan. She's like the real estate agent pretending to be objective when she gives you a tour of an unmitigated dump and saying, oh, it's a charming fixer upper. No, this is a dump. All right. I think that this is going to be a huge boon to Trump. We're already seeing it in the swing states, and I think they might be setting him up for a landslide. It's like when you watch a running back, like Franco Harris or Earl Campbell going towards the end zone carrying seven or eight people. The resistance becomes the momentum. He is turning the resistance into momentum that is carrying him forward. That's a football analogy, America.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Hey, Emily.

utterances.speaker: EMILY COMPAGNO, GUEST CO-HOST
utterances.utterance: Beast mode. Well, if I can just say that what I thought was peeled back today was a really interesting illustration of how important process and old guard and new guard is to a lot of these structures. And I was brought in when I was a federal managing attorney to a certain office and essentially to clean house. But what I was doing was inheriting an existing structure and an existing process and trying to kind of put a new guard in. And it is a struggle that it's really difficult to convey, I think, the weight of that old guard and the weight of the process and how strongly, as we saw today, for example, and most especially from Dr. Hill, who says, look, this is the way that we are used to and the reason we are is because it works. So the question for Americans and for right now, congressmen, is whether or not the disruption of that process is in a way that they find impeachable.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Impeachable? You mean whether or not the evidence presented this week, the Sondland testimony about quid pro quo? The people say that's enough or not enough. What do you say?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Whether these representatives feel that in this fact-finding week, that they have enough to go on to make their informed decisions, personally representing their constituents to make the vote. That would be the next step.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: All right. Up next, more reaction to this week's impeachment hearings.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Impeachment circus wrapping up this week as the media continues to embarrass themselves over and over again, every hour of coverage contains some kind of bombshell or it's explosive testimony. But the next one really takes the cake. CNN's Chris Cuomo clearly inspired by my highly acclaimed mom text series. Why are you laughing? So, he called his own mom on live TV to prove how easy it is to overhear a call like today's witness claims he did with Trump. Listen:

utterances.speaker: CHRIS CUOMO
utterances.utterance: Can you just say hello? Mom. She probably can't hear me. Mom, can you hear me?

utterances.speaker: MATILDA CUOMO
utterances.utterance: Yes, I hear you. When you talk to me, I hear you.

utterances.speaker: CHRIS CUOMO
utterances.utterance: I'm talking to you. Say hello to Dana Bash.

utterances.speaker: DANA BASH
utterances.utterance: Hi, Mrs. Cuomo. How are you?

utterances.speaker: CHRIS CUOMO
utterances.utterance: All right.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That's gold, Greg. I don't know his best part of the coverage.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Chris Cuomo is the master of the self own. Whenever he goes for a joke, he's incapable of seeing that he's the butt of his own jokes, which makes me laugh. But you know what I mean, to your point about everything like an explosive turning point. This is going to be the day that changes everything. This is porn for people who lost their sex drive in 2016.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: There's a pill for that, I think.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: think it advertises on Fox.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: All right, Dana, one of the reasons I think that they haven't been able to persuade not only Republicans, but the regular American people is because you can watch these hearings yourself. You could see them. You don't need to hear CNN or ABC tell you what to think. You can watch. And if you watch just for an hour, you don't see bombshells. You don't see explosive testimony. So, you know, you're being lied to when you tune in later for analysis.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: So, yeah, it's interesting because so Fox News has had tremendous viewership throughout this entire thing. And it's not because we've been on TV the entire time, even though I'm sure that's why they would like to tune in. People are genuinely interested. The results so far that have come back from the public opinion surveys about how they're feeling about impeachment, both nationally and in some of the battleground states have shown that the Democrats are basically not persuading America that the president should be impeached. And I don't think that means that there's not going to be a close election, or it could mean that the president ultimately wins in a landslide. It's too early to tell. But I think that most voters are thinking, let's move on, let's fight this out in November of 2020.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: 'Yeah. Juan, one of the reasons -- it's not a persuadable case, it's very complex. There's a lot of different layers. You have WMD, Watergate, Lewinsky, Iran Contra -- you can explain that to an eight-year-old, maybe not the Lewinsky thing, but you can expect that to a very young person. This, you know, you can watch hours of this hearing and you still don't know what's going.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Really?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yeah. Even the people testifying don't know what's going on.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, that's clear from your perspective.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Sondland yesterday -- I don't know what was up.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I'll tell you what struck me today was Republicans stop questioning Hill and Holmes. Instead, they went into these kinds of partisan rants. And it was like at the end that they're just ranting at the witness because they don't want to hear anything to do with facts. It's like Republicans -- oh, she didn't have a fact?

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- she got fired this summer before the whole thing started.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: She had a lot of facts. She had a lot of --.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: She got fired a long time.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Dana's upset.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: I'm not upset.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Okay. I thought -- you said you don't like her being tracked. I don't like her being tracked because -- she was a strong candidate. I think witness Yovanovitch strong. What Fiona Hill said was, I'm here as a fact witness. It's up to you, the Congress, to decide about impeachment. But she said, you know what? I chose to go into the Trump administration. Here's what happened with my boss, John Bolton. Here's what I heard. Here's meetings I went into to say, you guys can't do this here. It's inappropriate. You're pursuing a separate channel. And then to hear how she was attacked, how she is said to be -- I think it's Roger Stone and Alex Jones. Oh, she's a George Soros plant. Well, I mean, this is just --

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I don't know if she's a George Soros plan. I think when she says I don't like politics, Emily, getting involved in diplomacy, I mean, Barack Obama pulled out of -- he lied about Benghazi. Barack Obama spied on Donald Trump -- politics. No one blew the whistle then.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: The only way to find the whistle was too short. Listen, here is what happened in the federal government while the viewers of mainstream media were subjected to these impeachment hearings and our tax dollars are pouring in. We what we did this week on Wednesday, the Senate confirmed the first Cuban American woman judge of the 11th Circuit, which shifted that balance toward the GOP's favor. And that's the third court that has been shifted and flipped during this administration. That's a big deal. A veteran suicide bill made great strides this week as well. And in a state that really matters for this election, which is Wisconsin. We got that poll that came out yesterday that said Trump is head-to-head or surpassed all of the Dems that are leading and most importantly, the majority of voters there oppose impeachment. So, in a state that really matters, no one cares about this.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Alright. We're going to move on from impeachment, alright? Because the Democrats had a debate last night. You might not even know. Greg has got the whole thing next.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: The clown car rolled into Atlanta, dropping off a pile of broken toys minus the batteries. There was Gramps, who sounded like a 10-year-old coming down from the laughing gas after getting a tooth pulled:

utterances.speaker: JOE BIDEN
utterances.utterance: The next president of the United States is going to have to do to two things. Defeat Donald Trump. That's number one. And number two, it's going to have to be able to go into states like Georgia and North Carolina and other places and get a Senate majority.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Maybe it's not his fault. He did just find out he was a grandfather. Then there was the cop pretending to be something she's not:

utterances.speaker: KAMALA HARRIS
utterances.utterance: I think that it's unfortunate that we have someone on the stage who is attempting to be the Democratic nominee for president of the United States, who during the Obama administration spent four years full-time on Fox News criticizing President Obama.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, it's unfortunate to have the guts to go on TV and face tough questions. Maybe you should throw her in jail. And who is this guy again?

utterances.speaker: TOM STEYER
utterances.utterance: But I'm different from everybody else on this stage. I'm the only person on this stage who will say that climate is the number one priority for me. I'm the only person on this stage who's spent decades building an international business. I'm the person who can do it.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Did someone leave John Kerry out in the sun? God, I miss Marianne and Swalwell. It would have been a gas. Dana. Yeah. But thank God they focused on child welfare.

utterances.speaker: AMY KLOBUCHAR
utterances.utterance: We should codify Roe v. Wade into law.

utterances.speaker: BERNIE SANDERS
utterances.utterance: Understand that it's women who control their own bodies, not politicians.

utterances.speaker: CORY BOOKER
utterances.utterance: This is a voting issue. This is a voter suppression issue.

utterances.speaker: ELIZABETH WARREN
utterances.utterance: I believe that abortion rights are human rights.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Nice. Yeah. In case you forgot, for Dems, abortion is the ultimate childcare. No need for a babysitter when there's no baby to sit. Bottom line, you could have found more fire in a bag of prunes. Impeachment theater drained them of energy and intelligence, leaving them all searching for something to say to each other than "orange man bad." None of them laid a glove on the other, which is good hygiene. But you know what the debate stage really was? It was that cabin at Camp Crystal Lake from Friday the 13th. And all of those candidates are the stupid teenagers making idiotic decisions. Let's check out the basement. Let's go skinny dipping alone. Above all, don't hop in that car to escape. And Trump. He's the ever-present Jason waiting to pick each and every one of them off. He's there on that stage, even when he isn't. You know, it's sad to think that someday Trump will not be president and the whole world will look like a Democratic debate. But like Jason, maybe we'll just keep bringing him back. Let's look at the positives. Juan, I thought Booker won. I thought that he expressed energy and brains, like he could be on stage. But do you think it's too late for him?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: No, it's not too late, because I think this is up in the air in many ways. But I don't know why you thought he won. If you were saying, oh, you know what, finally, one of the Democrats defended the rich because what he said was Elizabeth Warren going after, you know, a wealth tax on the rich, two percent on people who have billions and all -- he said, well, wait a second, no, the real way to do this to appeal to voters is to talk about wealth creation. How can we help you to become rich and the like? But I thought he was pretty much a non-factor early on, he didn't get much airtime. And I thought that if you were looking for a winner and loser scenario, I would say Pete Buttigieg, who is now the front runner in Iowa, at least, I don't think anybody went after him. I thought that Elizabeth Warren, again, it's not that she made any breakthroughs, but she stood there, and I think she occupied a lot of time, spoke a lot. And Bernie, again, I just don't think it changed anything. And if you look at the ratings, I don't think many people were --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's true. Jesse, it really kind of just laid there flat when you were watching it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I was actually laying flat while I was watching it.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: I thought it was the worst debate so far. I thought it was pathetic, bunch of platitudes. These people are unwatchable. They're boring. No one's breaking through with any clear policy. There's no, even, soundbites or sharp exchanges. I mean, they're talking about climate refugees? What is a climate refugee? It's too hot somewhere, so you pack up and move north? I mean, these things aren't real things that people care about in this country. I heard Biden answer that first question and I thought to myself, it's officially over for him. He had some dark energy going on last night. He looked medicated. I don't know what was coming out of his mouth. Bernie, you know, what you see is what you get. "The billionaires, the billion --" You know, OK. We know, Bernie, you hate billionaires. I mean and what's Biden doing punching down to Tom Steyer? Why is Kamala Harris punching down to Tulsi Gabbard? It's like these people don't even know how to win elections. Mayor Pete sitting there at 5 foot 3, you know, all polished. No one's laying a glove on him. He's surging. And they're not even pretending like they know what they're doing. Who is it? Booker acts like Barney, you know, the big purple guy, the cartoon. He's surprised that everything. Oh, gosh. Oh, golly. I mean, these are not really impressive candidates. And I think this impeachment thing is actually enhanced Donald Trump's aura. I mean, he's out there besieged by enemies, slaying dragons, slapping around China, killing terrorists. And these people are squabbling over climate refugees. So, it's over.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Emily, what do you -- anything to add to that?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: I think that said it all.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yeah, really.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: I felt like it was like when you see a sequel to a movie that just totally repeats the original movie, and it's so frustrating. And you're like this. There's nothing new.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: It's like Oceans 55.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Yes.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: No wait, wait. What about when Booker said that Biden must have been high when he said.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That was a great one.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: That was a good line.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Ahhh, ok, so you did watch.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: I did think it illustrated a little bit, but, probably --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: That's why I said it was good. Go ahead.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: But probably not to the extent that we didn't know already. But who gets flustered and who would shine or could hold their own, I should say, against President Trump?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, Dana?

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: That's what I felt like.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Two people. I think on Yang, he's like one of the only guys that's talking to, one of the only candidates, who is talking to the suburbs directly.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Right.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Like he understands the suburbs anxiety. He speaks to it, and he has ideas for how to deal with their anxieties, whether you like them or not. But he has talking to them that suburban group. And I think that's how he's able to maintain this like five or six percent. He's not going to be the nominee. But he sticks out there. And Mayor Pete seems to be the only one that is able to ad lib an attack.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Everybody else has things that are like well written out for them, so then they know when they're going to, you know, queue my line.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: It was hard to imagine last night how any of them gets to 270 electoral votes.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Yeah, interesting. But we're going to do it again in the next block. Coming up, Joe Biden's gaffes were so bad at the debate, even Democrats are calling him out.

utterances.speaker: JOE BIDEN
utterances.utterance: No man has a right to raise a hand to a woman in anger other than in self-defense. We have to change the culture, period, and keep punching at it and punching at it and punching at it. There will be a big -- I really mean it. I'm part of that Obama coalition. I come out of the black community in terms of my support. Three former chairs of the Black Caucus, the only African-American woman that had ever been elected to the United States Senate. A whole range of people.

utterances.speaker: CORY BOOKER
utterances.utterance: That's not true. That's not true.

utterances.speaker: KAMALA HARRIS

utterances.utterance: I said the first. I said the first African-American --

utterances.utterance: I wouldn't say that he was a house of fire in any of the debates that we've been been to. And yet he comes kind of bumps along, you know, kind of Mr. Magoo wing his way through this. And you keep worrying that he's going to hit a wall. But he's moving forward.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: And there it is true. He continues to move forward. Juan, his the early state polls, Iowa, New Hampshire, not so good. But across the board, you look at South Carolina in the national polls. Voters seem to think that he is the most electable against Donald Trump. That seems to be what they believe.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Right. And as he pointed out, Donald Trump is making the case for him. In that phone call with Zelensky, he says he wants dirt on not Bernie Sanders, not Elizabeth Warren. He wants dirt on guess who? Joe Biden.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Those words were never ever used.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Oh, yeah. He didn't say Biden's name? .Come on. Oh, please.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Read the perfect call transcript.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Are the Republicans just blind --.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: You can't make up stuff.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: But I will say this. I loved Axelrod's analogy, Mr. Magooing his way through, right? But you know, what's kind of baked in at this point with Joe Biden? I think people who like Joe Biden, who think he can beat Trump say, you know, we like this guy and we think he can do it. Now, I will say yes, at the debate, I thought the whole Medicare For All thing really was a moment, because you have President Obama saying we can't have revolution. We've got to have sort of incremental change. Bernie Sanders comes back and says, yeah, we've got to fix a broken, dysfunctional political system for the American people. And I think that's a real debate. I mean, it's almost like I'd like to see Bernie versus Obama on the stage.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Well, you kind of did, right? In 2016. I mean in that primary. But Bernie Sanders just says the same thing over and over again.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Yeah. I mean, Bernie is going to stay at 20, 19, 18. That's fine. And he'll take it all the way to the convention and just screw everything up. So, you know, keep donating. I mean, do what ever you want. I mean, Biden, you say the whole thing's baked in. I mean, it's gotten so baked in, people think he's high. I mean, Booker said it last night. What are you, high? You can't continue to make gaffes at this high of a level over and over and over again.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Wait a second, I thought you were a Trump supporter.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, I don't think winning the election is a gaffe. But I do think Biden looked embalmed last night. Who told him to squint and stare in a confused --

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Oh, it did really well in the focus group.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: -- over and over and over? And you know what? Listen, I feel sad for the guy. It was not a good night.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Okay, there was somebody else didn't have a great day yesterday. Deval Patrick. He was, of course, he was a governor of Massachusetts. utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Greg, do you feel bad?

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: I feel bad for the two people.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: They're like, boy, talk about picking the wrong guy. What are they going to do now?

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Well, I hope you don't talk about me like that.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: They hired a babysitter and everything. You know --

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- to Juan's point, which is right; there are a lot of times during 2015 and 2016 when I was like criticizing Trump for stuff he was saying, but it was -- people accepted it. They accepted that was part of who he is. I will say the difference. There's a parallel. Biden's gaffes betray a certain wobbliness, frailty. Trump's gaffes were like rude. He's rude, he's arrogant, whatever.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: He's punching too hard.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: He's punching too hard. In this, you don't even know if he could lift his arm up. And that's when you said you like you feel kind of like a little bad.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: The crowd was laughing with Trump when he was doing all that stuff.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Emily, let's give you the last word.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Well, yeah, I think that there is a difference between lucid and lucidity and lack of it and then when you just have no filter, those are the difference in the gaffes. utterances.utterance: But he's not raising that much.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: -- raising money, that's what I'm saying. So, at some point, these details have to catch up with the national polls.

utterances.utterance: It's a strange thing. I feel like last night was kind of a wash for the Democrats. I just think, OK, so last night was just the setup to December's debate, which is right before Christmas? I can't imagine that's going to make a big difference.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: I think a lot of people won't be there, tell you that. Well, you think that because the criteria --

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yeah.

utterances.utterance: -- gets higher. Well, maybe there will be fewer people on the stage. Alright, coming up, the fastest seven is back, and you don't want to miss what we have in store for you.

utterances.utterance: I don't care.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: -- you know, but they keep comparing stuff to toilet seats. It's all a myth.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Well, listen. Greg told me to do something. He said if your phone gets really dirty, just go clear your search history.

utterances.utterance: [laughs]

utterances.utterance: That's what you do, right? That's how to clean it up.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Oh, my.

utterances.speaker: GUTFELD
utterances.utterance: Did Dana even know?

utterances.utterance: Next topic. Most of us like a good nap. But should we be allowed to do it at work? utterances.utterance: I think that if you had to sit on set --.

utterances.speaker: WATTERS
utterances.utterance: Here we go.

utterances.utterance: - - for three days in a row, watching the hearings, that you should be allowed to take a nap. I totally think that's fair.

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yeah, I think this is a great idea.

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Even though I didn't sit there the whole day, but Martha MacCallum did. She should be allowed to have a nap.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: [laughs]

utterances.speaker: WILLIAMS
utterances.utterance: Yeah, I think that's a great idea. No, I mean, how ridiculous. I don't know, why even, I see now they have like rest areas in this office. Right? And I'm thinking for what?

utterances.speaker: PERINO
utterances.utterance: Prayer.

utterances.speaker: COMPAGNO
utterances.utterance: Well, for federal workers, everything is dictated. If you come in at 3:00, you leave at 7:00 or whatever.
